    {
        "content": "<p>Hello!</p>\n<p>I started reading Sheaves in Geometry and Logic and encountered the definition of a global section of a presheaf. I then wandered on the nlab I got confused about some terminology:</p>\n<p>For any category 𝓒 and object A: 𝓒, we have the following definitions:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Its <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/global+element\">global elements</a> := 𝓒(1, A), morphisms from the terminal object,</li>\n<li>Its <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/generalized+element\">generalized elements</a> := (U: 𝓒) × 𝓒(U, A), morphisms from any object.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>However, for any presheaf F: 𝓒ᵒᵖ→Set, we are given <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/limit#limit_of_a_setvalued_functor\">here</a> synonyms for limF := 𝓒ᵒᵖ→Set(1, F) as:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Its generalized elements, instead of talking about global elements like before.</li>\n<li>Its <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/global+section#GeneralTopos\">global sections</a>, where they indeed talk about the hom-set of global elements.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>I thought it may be a typo, but <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/generalized+element#in_presheaf_categories\">here</a> they say that \"the generalized elements of a presheaf F are the global sections of this presheaf\".</p>\n<p>So, do I miss something?</p>\n<p>Also, do local sections of F correspond to transformations U ⇒ F (what I'd call generalized elements)?</p>",
        "id": 454466204,
        "sender_full_name": "Sidney Congard",
        "timestamp": 1722081648
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>They mean in each case the generalized elements having the specified domain <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>I</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">I</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">I</span></span></span></span>. So if <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>I</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">I</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">I</span></span></span></span> is the terminal presheaf, you get global elements. But if <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>I</mi><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">C</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mo>−</mo><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>c</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">I = \\mathcal{C}(-, c)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">I</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05834em;\">C</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\">−</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">c</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>, then generalized elements over <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>I</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">I</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">I</span></span></span></span> are in natural bijection with elements of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>F</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>c</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">F(c)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">c</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>, by the Yoneda lemma.</p>",
        "id": 454467721,
        "sender_full_name": "Todd Trimble",
        "timestamp": 1722082955
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Usually the term \"local section\", as in the case of sheaves over a space, would refer to a generalized element whose domain <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>U</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">U</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">U</span></span></span></span> is a subobject of the terminal object.</p>",
        "id": 454467861,
        "sender_full_name": "Todd Trimble",
        "timestamp": 1722083091
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thank you for your answer! It still feels wrong to me to read e.g. \"The set limF is equivalently called [...] the set of generalized elements of F\" or \"the generalized elements of a presheaf F are the global sections of this presheaf\", where in both case we could (should?) say global elements instead...<br>\nFor representables, I take it that \"the generalized elements of F at stage d\" means the same as generalized elements over d i.e. with domain d?</p>",
        "id": 454469945,
        "sender_full_name": "Sidney Congard",
        "timestamp": 1722084732
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But they <em>are</em> global sections!  Sections of what? Sections of the unique map <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>F</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">F \\to t</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6151em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span></span></span></span> where <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">t</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6151em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span></span></span></span> denotes the terminal object. Every global element <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>t</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>F</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">x: t \\to F</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6151em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span></span></span></span> is a section of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">!</mo><mo>:</mo><mi>F</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">!: F \\to t</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mclose\">!</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6151em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span></span></span></span>, i.e., the composite <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>∘</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">!</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">x \\circ !</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mord\">∘</span><span class=\"mclose\">!</span></span></span></span> is the identity on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">t</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6151em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span></span></span></span>, by terminality of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">t</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6151em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span></span></span></span>. </p>\n<p>It's just using different words to describe the same thing.</p>",
        "id": 454470259,
        "sender_full_name": "Todd Trimble",
        "timestamp": 1722085059
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"277611\">Todd Trimble</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/Generalized.20elements.20.26.20sections.20of.20presheaves/near/454470259\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>But they <em>are</em> global sections!  Sections of what? Sections of the unique map <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>F</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">F \\to t</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6151em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span></span></span></span> where <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">t</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6151em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span></span></span></span> denotes the terminal object. Every global element <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>t</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>F</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">x: t \\to F</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6151em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span></span></span></span> is a section of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">!</mo><mo>:</mo><mi>F</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">!: F \\to t</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mclose\">!</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6151em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span></span></span></span>, i.e., the composite <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>∘</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">!</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">x \\circ !</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mord\">∘</span><span class=\"mclose\">!</span></span></span></span> is the identity on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">t</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6151em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span></span></span></span>, by terminality of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">t</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6151em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span></span></span></span>. </p>\n<p>It's just using different words to describe the same thing.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Yeah I agree with that and I understand the correspondance between global elements &amp; global sections, what I don't understand is when \"the generalized elements\" is used to speak about global sections, or global elements. Do we agree that <em>generalized</em> elements are not the same as global sections?</p>",
        "id": 454479392,
        "sender_full_name": "Sidney Congard",
        "timestamp": 1722091540
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>E.g. I can take a presheaf that has no global elements i.e. no global sections, it still has generalized elements</p>",
        "id": 454479847,
        "sender_full_name": "Sidney Congard",
        "timestamp": 1722091711
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So the sentence \"The set limF is equivalently called [...] the set of generalized elements of F\" from the nlab sounds wrong to me</p>",
        "id": 454480102,
        "sender_full_name": "Sidney Congard",
        "timestamp": 1722091820
    },
    {
        "content": "<blockquote>\n<p>Do we agree that <em>generalized</em> elements are not the same as global sections?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Yes, of course, but what I was trying to say in my first comment is that you clipped out some context from the nLab discussion, like the specific examples of $I$ being discussed. I mean, I think you're right that the exposition could be slightly improved, but if you read the entirety of the subsection <em>In Presheaf Categories</em>, and the two subsections before that, it's clear from context that when they say \"generalized elements\" within a paragraph, they mean over the domain $I$ currently under discussion, not generalized elements over arbitrary domains. For example, in the first paragraph of <em>In Presheaf Categories</em>, read that as generalized elements over <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>I</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">I</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">I</span></span></span></span> = terminal presheaf.</p>",
        "id": 454490274,
        "sender_full_name": "Todd Trimble",
        "timestamp": 1722096613
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Oh okay, reading it again that seems right indeed. However, in <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/limit#limit_of_a_setvalued_functor\">the section from limits</a>, I don't think I've removed important context here no?</p>",
        "id": 454491067,
        "sender_full_name": "Sidney Congard",
        "timestamp": 1722096957
    },
    {
        "content": "<blockquote>\n<p>The limit of a Set-valued functor F:Dᵒᵖ→Set is the hom-set (pt, F) where pt is the functor constant on the point, i.e. the terminal diagram.<br>\nThe set limF is equivalently called<br>\n - the set of global sections of F;<br>\n - the set of generalized elements of F.</p>\n</blockquote>",
        "id": 454491314,
        "sender_full_name": "Sidney Congard",
        "timestamp": 1722097029
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Oof. No, you haven't missed anything; that last bullet point really ought to be reworded, because it is very likely to confuse some people (even if we generously supply some context mentally). Thanks for bringing to attention. I need to get on the road, but if no one edits it first, I'll fix it later.</p>",
        "id": 454492297,
        "sender_full_name": "Todd Trimble",
        "timestamp": 1722097302
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Aaah I was definitely among the confused people <span aria-label=\"sweat smile\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f605\" role=\"img\" title=\"sweat smile\">:sweat_smile:</span> <span aria-label=\"relieved\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f60c\" role=\"img\" title=\"relieved\">:relieved:</span></p>",
